An '''anatopism''' (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''ana'', "against," and ''topos'', "place") is something that is out of its proper place.  Thus, for example, a modern [[electronic computer]] would be an anatopism in [[ancient Rome]].

==Anatopism in literature==
The [[Poland|Polish]] writer [[Bolesław Prus]] introduces, in chapter 63 of his [[historical novel]] ''[[Pharaoh (novel)|Pharaoh]]'', set in the [[ancient Egypt|ancient ''Egypt'']] of 1085 B.C.E., a substance that behaves like [[gunpowder]], which is known to have been invented in ''[[China]]''; this is evidently an anatopism.  Prus similarly introduces other anatopisms, for example, something whose action resembles that of a [[telescope]], which would appear also to be an [[anachronism]].

